formula: a(n+1) = 2^n*(5*2^n - 1) for all n >= 0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 03 2012

formula: The binomial transform of A084214(n+1) is A020989(n).
a(n) = a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) for n > 2. - _Klaus Brockhaus_, Dec 01 2009

A084215.name: Expansion of g.f.: (1+x^2)/(1-2*x).
formula: a(n) is the sum of top row terms of M^n, M = an infinite square production matrix as follows:
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) for n >= 3, a(0) = 1, a(1) = 2, a(2) = 5. - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 13 2013

A084216.name: a(n) = smallest integer d such that a quadratic representation (2n+1)= x^2+ d*y^2 exists (x,y positive integers).

A084217.name: Number of k's 1<=k<=n dividing the numerator of 2n-th Bernoulli number.

A084221.name: a(n+2) = 4*a(n), with a(0)=1, a(1)=3.
formula: a(n) = A133628(n)-A133628(n-1) for n>1. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Sep 19 2007
Equals A133080 * [1, 2, 4, 8,...]. Row sums of triangle A133087. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Sep 08 2007
a(n+1)-2a(n) = A000079 signed. a(n)+a(n+2)=5*a(n). First differences give A135520. - _Paul Curtz_, Apr 22 2008

A084222.name: a(n) = -2*a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2), with a(0)=1, a(1)=2.
formula: For n > 1, abs(a(n) - a(n+1)) = 3^n. - _Amarnath Murthy_ and Meenakshi Srikanth (menakan_s(AT)yahoo.com), Jul 15 2003; corrected by _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 16 2007
a(n) = 9*a(n-2) - 10 with a(0) = 1 and a(1) = 2. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 24 2014

A084223.name: Numerators of successive approximations to zeta(3) = Sum_{k>0} 1/k^3, using Zeilberger's formula with s=2.
formula: a(n) = numerator( Sum_{k=1..n} (1/4)*(-1)^(k-1)*(56*k^2 - 32*k + 5)/((2*k - 1)^2* binomial(3*k, k)*binomial(2*k, k)*k^3). - _G. C. Greubel_, Oct 08 2018

A084224.name: Denominators of successive approximations to zeta(3) = Sum_{k>0} 1/k^3, using Zeilberger's formula with s=2.
formula: a(n) = denominator( Sum_{k=1..n} (1/4)*(-1)^(k-1)*(56*k^2-32*k+5)/((2*k-1)^2 * binomial(3*k,k) * binomial(2*k,k) * k^3) ). - _G. C. Greubel_, Oct 08 2018

A084225.name: Numerators of successive approximations to zeta(3) = Sum_{k>0} 1/k^3, using Zeilberger's formula with s=3.

A084226.name: Denominators of successive approximations to zeta(3) = Sum_{k>0} 1/k^3, using Zeilberger's formula with s=3.

A084227.name: Numbers of the form p*q^k with distinct primes p and q, k>0.
formula: a(n) ~ n log n/log log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 19 2015

A084228.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=2; thereafter a(n) = sum of digits of (a(1)+a(2)+a(3)+...+a(n-1)).

A084231.name: Numbers k such that the root-mean-square value of 1, 2, ..., k, i.e., sqrt((1/k)*Sum_{j=1..k} j^2), is an integer.

A084233.name: Decimal expansion of area under the curve Zeta(1/2 + t*I) from zero to its first nontrivial zero (A058303).

A084235.name: Smallest k such that |M(k)| = 2^n, where M(x) is Mertens's function A002321.

A084236.name: a(n) = M(2^n), where M(n) is Mertens's function, A002321.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..2^n} mu(k), where mu = Moebius function (A008683).

A084237.name: a(n) = M(10^n), where M(n) is Mertens's function.
formula: Mertens's function: Sum_{k=1..n} mu(k), where mu = Möbius function (A008683).

A084238.name: Least k such that log(k) < k^(1/n).
formula: For n = 1, a(n) = 1. For n>=2, a(n) = ceiling(e^(-(n+1)*W-1(-1/(n+1)))) where W-1(x) is the Lambert W function with branch -1. - _Wong Ching Yin_, Feb 26 2021

A084239.name: Rank of K-groups of Furstenberg transformation group C*-algebras of n-torus.
formula: a(n) = constant term of prod(i=1, n, 1+t^(i-.5(n+1))) for odd n and a(n) = constant term of (1+t^(.5))*prod(i=1, n, 1+t^(i-.5(n+1))) for even n.

Sums of antidiagonals of A067059, i.e. a(n) is sum over k of number of partitions of [k(n-k)/2] into up to k parts each no more than n-k. Close to 2^(n+1)*sqrt(6/(pi*n^3)) and seems to be even closer to something like 2^(n+1)*sqrt(6/(pi*(n^3+0.9*n^2-0.1825*n+1.5))). - _Henry Bottomley_, Jul 20 2003

A084242.name: Least k, 1<= k <=n, such that the number of elements of the continued fraction for n/k is maximum.
formula: k>1, a(F(k))=F(k-1) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number; probably, limit n ->oo 1/n*sum(k=1, n, a(k)) = 1/phi where phi is the Golden ratio (1+sqrt(5))/2

A084247.name: a(n) = -a(n-1) + 2a(n-2), a(0)=1, a(1)=2.
formula: (-1)^(n+1)*a(n) = A078008(n+1)-A078008(n). [apart from signs the second differences of A001045]. - _Paul Curtz_, Jun 30 2008, Feb 24 2021

A084248.name: Decimal expansion of c = Product_{k>=1} (1 + 1/t(k)) where t(k) = k(k+1)/2 is the k-th triangular number.

A084251.name: G.f.: A(x) = exp(sum(n>=1, A084250(n)*x^n/n)), where A084250 lists the least distinct positive integers that allow A(x) to be an integer power series.

A084252.name: A measure of how close r^n is to an integer where r is the real root of x^3-x-1, i.e.. r = (1/2 + sqrt(23/108))^(1/3) + (1/2 - sqrt(23/108))^(1/3) = 1.3247.... (Higher absolute value of a(n) means closer, negative means less than closest integer.)

A084253.name: a(n) is the denominator of the coefficient of z^(2n-1) in the Maclaurin expansion of Sqrt[Pi]Erfi[z].

A084256.name: Decimal expansion of x such that x^2 + x^3 + x^5 + x^7 + x^11 + x^13 + x^17 + ... = 1.

A084260.name: Triangular numbers that set a new record for number of triangular divisors.

A084261.name: A binomial transform of factorial numbers.
formula: a_n ~ (1/2) * sqrt(Pi*n/e)*(n/2)^(n/2)*exp(-n/2 + sqrt(2n)). - Cecil C Rousseau (ccrousse(AT)memphis.edu), Mar 14 2006: (cf. A002896).

A084262.name: Binomial transform of double factorials.
formula: Let M be the infinite bidiagonal matrix with M(r,r)=1 in the main diagonal, M(r,r+1) = 2r-1, r>=1, odd integers in the superdiagonal, and with the rest zeros. a(n) is the sum of first row terms of M^n. Example: a(4) = 188 = 1 + 4 + 18 + 60 + 105. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 24 2011
G.f.: 1/G(0) where G(k) =1 - 2*x*(2*k+1) - 2*x^2*(k+1)*(2*k+1)/G(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 12 2013
G.f.: 1/(1-x)/Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 - x/(1-x)*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 19 2013
G.f.: conjecture: T(0)/(1-x), where T(k) = 1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+1) - (1-x)/T(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 13 2013

A084264.name: Binomial transform of A084263.
formula: a(n) = 2^(n-3)*(n^2+3*n+4) for n > 0. - _Eric W. Weisstein_, Sep 30 2017

A084267.name: Partial sums of a binomial quotient.

formula: Primes p(j) such that (p(j)+p(j+1))/2 = q(m)^w, where q(m) is a prime.

A084291.name: Difference between consecutive primes arising after difference (d=2) between twin primes. In A001223, terms following those ones which equal to two.

A084294.name: Number of primes in the interval [prime(n),n+prime(n)].
formula: a(n) = Pi(n+prime(n)) - n + 1 = A000720(n+A000040(n)) - n + 1. [corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Aug 28 2019]

A084295.name: n is such that pi(n*prime(n))/n is an integer.

A084296.name: Triangle: number of distinct prime factors in n-th primorial numbers when n prime factors first appears and in n-1 subsequent integers after.

A084297.name: Primes p=prime(m) such that pi(m*p)/m is integer.

A084315.name: a(n) = x is the smallest number such that gcd(prime(x)-1,x-1) = n.

A084316.name: a(n) is the smallest number x such that gcd(prime(x)+1,x+1) = n.

formula: a(n) = a(squarefree kernel of n) = a(n^k) for any power k >= 1.

A084318.name: Iterate function described in A084317 if started at initial value n until reaching a fixed point.

A084319.name: Orbit of 91 under function described in A084317.

A084320.name: Number of powers of two between 2 consecutive factorials (2! including).
formula: a(n) = A000523(n) + O(1). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 26 2013

A084321.name: Least number k such that between k! and (k+1)! there are n powers of 2.

A084322.name: Fixed points if prime-factor-concatenation function (A084318) is iterated at primorial number initial values.

A084323.name: Fixed points reached when prime-factor-concatenation function [A084317] is started at n!.

A084324.name: Palindromic numbers that set a new record for number of palindromic divisors.

A084325.name: Palindromes such that at least one divisor is non-palindromic; palindromes not in A062687.

A084326.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n) = 6*a(n-1)-4*a(n-2).
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*sum(k = 0, n, binomial(n, k)*F(3*k)) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number.
a(n) = Sum(C(n, 2k+1)5^k 3^(n-2k-1), k = 0, .., Floor[(n-1)/2]). a(n) = 2^(n-1)F(2n). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Jul 22 2004

a(n) is the rightmost term in M^n * [1 0] where M is the 2X2 matrix [5 1 / 1 1]. The characteristic polynomial of M = x^2 - 6x + 4. a(n)/a(n-1) tends to (3 + sqrt(5)), a root of the polynomial and an eigenvalue of M. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 16 2004
a(n) = sum{k = 0..n, sum{j = 0..n, C(n, j)C(j, k)F(j+k)/2}}. - _Paul Barry_, Feb 14 2005

If p[i] = (4^i-1)/3, and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j] = p[j-i+1], (i <= j), A[i,j] = -1, (i = j+1), and A[i,j] = 0 otherwise. Then, for n >= 1, a(n) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010

A084328.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1; a(n) = 13*a(n-1) - 11*a(n-2).
formula: a(n) = (1/5)*Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*F(5*k) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number.

A084329.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n)=20a(n-1)-20a(n-2).
formula: a(n)=(1/8)*sum(k=0, n, binomial(n, k)*F(6*k)) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number.

A084330.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = 31*a(n-1) - 29*a(n-2).
formula: a(n) = (1/13)*sum(k=0, n, binomial(n, k)*F(7*k)) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number.

A084331.name: a(1) = 2; a(n+1) is the least prime p not already used such that |p-a(n)| is not equal to |a(k+1)-a(k)| for any k < n.

A084334.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) is the least squarefree m not already used such that |m-a(n)| is not equal to |a(k+1)-a(k)| for any k < n.

A084335.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) is the least composite number m not already used such that |m-a(n)| is not equal to |a(k+1)-a(k)| for any k < n.

A084336.name: a(n) is the smallest composite number not already in the sequence such that the absolute values of the successive differences are distinct primes.

A084337.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers so that the successive ratios ( of the larger to the smaller term) are all distinct integers. a(m)/a(m-1)= a(k)/a(k-1) iff m = k ( assuming a(m) > a(m-1) otherwise the ratio a(m-1)/a(m) is to be considered). Priority is given to smallest number not included earlier than to the successive ratio that has not occurred earlier.

A084342.name: Digit reversal of n concatenated with n mod n.

A084345.name: Numbers with a nonprime number of 1's in their binary expansion (complement of A052294).

A084346.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives decomposition of Fib(n)*Fib(n+1) into non-adjacent Fibonacci numbers (given by their indices).

A084348.name: Triangle in which row n gives periodic part of a certain map.

A084349.name: Squarefree numbers that are not the sum of two squares.

A084351.name: Length of period of sequences r(k,n)=floor(sin(1)*k!)-n*floor(sin(1)*k!/n) when n is fixed.
formula: For n>1 a(n)=n if n==0 (mod 4), a(n)=2n is n==0 (mod 2) and n is not divisible by 4, a(n)=4n if n is odd.

A084352.name: Minimum digit out of both prime factors of palindromic brilliant numbers.

A084353.name: Palindromes such that the product of the nonzero digits + 1 is prime.

A084354.name: Primes whose product of nonzero digits + 1 is prime.

A084355.name: Least number of positive cubes needed to represent n!.

A084357.name: Number of sets of sets of lists.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(exp(x/(1-x))-1). Lah transform of Bell numbers: Sum_{k=0..n} n!/k!*binomial(n-1, k-1)*Bell(k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 28 2003

A084358.name: Lists of sets of lists.
formula: a(n) = n!*Lag{n,(.)!*Lag[.,P(.,2),0],-1} = P(n,2) - n*P(n-1,2) umbrally, where P(j,t) are the polynomials in A131758 and Lag(n,x,a) are the associated Laguerre polynomials of order a; that is, the sequence is given by an iterated combinatorial Laguerre transform, of mixed order, of a set of polynomials related to the polylogarithms, which reduces to a simple finite difference. - _Tom Copeland_, Sep 30 2007
E.g.f.: 1/(2-exp(x/(1-x))). Lah transform of preferential arrangements: Sum_{k=0..n} n!/k!*binomial(n-1, k-1)*A000670(k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 28 2003

A084359.name: a(n) = number of partitions of n into pair of parts n=p+q, p>=q>=1, with p-q equal to a square >= 0.

A084360.name: Number of partitions of n into pair of parts whose difference is a prime.
formula: a(n) = ( pi(n-1)-2 )*( n mod 2 ) + 1 + floor(1/n) - floor(n/2)*floor(2/n). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Feb 01 2013
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..floor(n/2)} A010051(n-2i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 10 2018

A084361.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) is the least prime of the form (2^k)*a(n)+-1, for some positive k.

A084362.name: a(n) = Sum{j_1 + ... + j_n = n} Sum_{k=1..n} k*C(n-1,k-1), where the outer sum is over all partitions of n.

A084364.name: Define the operations M: multiply by 11, D: divide by 11, R: reverse digits. Sequence gives trajectory of 19 under action of M,R,D,R.

A084365.name: Squarefree kernel of numbers that are not prime powers.

A084368.name: Prime(n) does not contain the digit 1.

A084369.name: Numbers n such that the n-th prime number doesn't contain any even digits.

A084370.name: Convolution of odd primes with themselves.

A084372.name: Least composite k such that nearest integer to average of smallest and largest prime factors of k equals n.

A084373.name: Numbers n such that smallest digit of n = total number of divisors of n.

A084374.name: Smallest digit of n = number of prime divisors of n (counted with multiplicity).

A084375.name: Indices of primes which remain prime if any one digit is deleted (leading zeros allowed).

A084377.name: a(n) = n^3 + 7.
formula: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4) for n>3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Jun 10 2016

A084378.name: a(n) = n^3 + 3.
formula: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4) for n>3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Jun 10 2016

A084381.name: a(n) = n^3 + 5.
formula: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4) for n>3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Jun 09 2016

A084383.name: a(0)=0; for n>0, a(n) = smallest number that is not a concatenation of any number of distinct earlier terms in increasing order.

A084384.name: a(1) = 2; a(n+1) = smallest k > a(n) that is divisible by at most (1/2)*[tau(k)] previous terms.

A084385.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) is the smallest number not occurring earlier and coprime to sum(j=1,n, a(j)).
formula: For n > 6: a(n) = n - 2 for (n mod 4) = 0, a(n) = n - 1 for (n mod 4) = 1, a(n) = n + 1 for (n mod 4) = 2, a(n) = n + 2 for (n mod 4) = 3. - Klaus Brockhaus, Nov 30 2003.

A084386.name: Number of pairs of rabbits when there are 3 pairs per litter and offspring reach parenthood after 3 gestation periods; a(n) = a(n-1) + 3*a(n-3), with a(0) = a(1) = a(2) = 1.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-2*k, k)*3^k. - _Paul Barry_, Nov 18 2003
G.f.: W(0)/2, where W(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(1 + 3*x^2)/(x*(1 + 3*x^2) + 1/W(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 28 2013
Starting (1 + x + 4*x^2 + ...), is the INVERT transform of (1 + 3*x^2). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 27 2017

A084388.name: Solutions k for n^3 + m = k^2.

A084389.name: Solutions n for n^3 + m = k^2.

A084390.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integer > a(n-1) with exactly n letters when spelled in English.

A084391.name: For n>3, a(n) = smallest number divisible by exactly n-2 previous terms; a(n)=n for n<=3.

A084392.name: For k not divisible by 10, let f(k) be the number obtained by moving the last digit of k to the front. Then a(n) is the smallest k > 0, made of nonzero digits, such that for all 1 <= i < n, i+1 divides f^i(k).

A084393.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that the n-th term is coprime to n and the sum of n terms starting from the n-th term is a multiple of n.

A084394.name: Sum of n terms starting with the n-th term of A084393.

A084396.name: a(1) = 1; then numbers in increasing order such that the n-th partial concatenation is divisible by n.

A084397.name: a(n) = n-th partial concatenation of A084396(n) divided by n.

A084398.name: Except for a(1) = 1, rearrangement of natural numbers such that a(n) is not equal to n, but the prime signature of a(n) is the same as that of n.

A084400.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = smallest number that does not divide the product of all previous terms.

A084401.name: n-th partial product + 1 is a prime, where a(n)>1 for n>1.

A084402.name: n-th partial product - 1 is a prime, where a(n) > 1.

A084403.name: Primes arising in A084402. a(n) = n-th partial product of A084402 - 1.

A084404.name: Numbers n such that n#*2^n+1 is prime, where n# = product of primes <= n.

A084405.name: Primes such that the sum of the factorials of the digits is also prime.

A084406.name: Numbers k such that k#*2^k-1 is prime, where k# = product of primes <= k.

A084407.name: Number of decimal places to which the n-th convergent of continued fraction expansion of Pi matches with the correct value.

A084408.name: Triangle read by rows: if n is prime, row n contains the n smallest primes not already used; if n is composite, row n contains the n smallest composite numbers not already used. A permutation of the positive integers.

A084409.name: Main diagonal of triangle A084408.
formula: For n prime, a(n) = p(A034387(n)). For n composite, a(n) = A002808([n*(n+1)/2]-A034387(n)-1).

A084410.name: First column of triangle A084408.
formula: For n prime, a(n) = p(A034387(n)-n+1). For n composite, a(n) = A002808([n*(n+1)/2]-A034387(n)-n).

A084412.name: Least palindromic prime that strictly encloses the n-th palindromic prime, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084413.name: Smallest prime with "n" as central digit(s), or -1 if no such prime exists.
formula: If n is prime, then a(n) = n, else a(n) = A084414(n). - _Michel Marcus_, Oct 05 2013

A084414.name: Smallest prime > n having "n" as central digits(s), or -1 if no such prime exists.

A084416.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = Sum_{i=k..n} i!*Stirling2(n,i), n >= 1, 1 <= k <= n.
formula: E.g.f. for m-th column: (exp(x)-1)^m/(2-exp(x)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 14 2003

A084418.name: Numbers n with property that n sets a new record for number of ways to write n as the sum of a brilliant number and a prime.

A084419.name: a(n) = number of primes that can be formed by adding 1 to the product of any subset of the divisors of n.

A084420.name: Least number k such that between k! and (k+1)! there are n powers of ten.

A084422.name: Number of subsets of integers 1 through n (including the empty set) containing no pair of integers that share a common factor.

A084423.name: Set partitions up to rotations.
formula: a(p) = (Bell(p)+2*(p-1))/p for prime p; cf. A079609. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 04 2003

U(k,j) = 1 if k=0, else Sum_{i=1..k} C(k-1,i-1) Sum_{d|j} U(k-i,j)*d^{i-1}. Then a(n) = (Sum_{j|n} phi(j)*U(n/j,j))/n. (U(k,j) is the number of partitions invariant under a permutation with k cycles of j objects each.) - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jun 09 2008
a(n) = [n==0] + [n>0] * (1/n) * Sum_{d|n} phi(d) * A162663(n/d,d). - _Robert A. Russell_, Jun 10 2018

A084424.name: Odd numbers having odd numbers of prime factors, odd sums of prime factors and odd sums of decimal digits.

A084425.name: Let b(0) = n, b(2*k+1) = c, where c > b(m) is the smallest number such that gcd(c,b(2*k))=1, b(2*k+2) = e where e < b(m) is the smallest number such that gcd(e,b(2*k+1))=1 for m = 0..2*k, until reaching e = 1. Then a(n) = the last c.

A084427.name: Gregorian calendar years with Ascension Day in April.

A084428.name: Numbers n such that n 7's followed by n is prime.

A084429.name: Integers m such that the base-10 digit concatenation 4//m//3//m//2//m//1 is prime.

A084430.name: Smallest prime with "n^3" as central digit(s).

A084433.name: Numbers all whose cyclic permutations have GCD > 1.

A084434.name: Numbers whose digit permutations have GCD > 1.

A084435.name: a(1) = 2, then smallest prime of the form 2^k*a(n-1) + 1.

A084436.name: Smallest prime which is one more than the square of a squarefree number with n prime divisors.

A084438.name: Positive integers n such that n!!! - 1 = A007661(n) - 1 is prime.

A084439.name: Number of triangular partitions of n of order 3.

A084440.name: Number of ways to write the n-th prime as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>0.

A084441.name: Primes that can be written as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>0.

A084442.name: Primes that can be written uniquely as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>0.

A084443.name: Primes that can be written in more than one way as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>0.

A084444.name: Primes that can be written as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>1.

A084445.name: Primes that cannot be written as 1+p+p^k, p prime and k>0.

A084446.name: Number of triangular partitions of n of order 4.

A084447.name: Number of triangular partitions of n of order 5.

A084448.name: Decimal expansion of (negative of) Kinkelin constant.
formula: Equals (1 - gamma - log(2*Pi))/12 + Zeta'(2)/(2*Pi^2), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 25 2015
Equals 1/24 - gamma/3 - Sum_{k>=1} (zeta(2*k+1)-1)/((2*k+1)*(2*k+3)) = 1/12 - log(A), where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant (A074962) (Kinkelin, 1860).

A084449.name: Positions of sevens (ground states) in A084451.

A084451.name: Juggling states associated with the juggling sequence A084452.

A084452.name: An infinite juggling sequence with three balls: a(n) is zero when A084451(n-1) is even, otherwise the least (lowest) throw such that the resulting next juggling state A084451(n) does not occur in A084451[0..n-1].

A084455.name: Permutation of Z, obtained by reflecting the juggling sequence A084452 from positive to negative numbers (with zero thrown at beat 0), folded to N with functions N2Z and Z2N.

A084457.name: Juggling states associated with the juggling sequence A084458.

A084458.name: An infinite juggling sequence using three balls: a(n) is the least (lowest) throw needed to ensure that none of the juggling states A084457[n..n+A006519(n)-1] occurs in A084457[0..n-1].

A084461.name: Permutation of Z, obtained by reflecting the juggling sequence A084458 from positive to negative numbers (with zero thrown at beat 0), folded to N with functions N2Z and Z2N.

A084463.name: Positions of even juggling states in A084457, i.e., positions of zeros in A084458 - 1.

A084464.name: Positions of odd juggling states in A084457, i.e., positions of nonzero-throws in A084458 - 1.

A084468.name: Odd numbers with exactly 3 ones in binary expansion.

A084471.name: Change 0 to 00 in binary representation of n.

A084472.name: Write n in binary and replace 0 with 00.

A084473.name: Replace 0 with 0000 in binary representation of n.

A084474.name: Write n in binary and replace 0 with 0000.

A084475.name: a(n) defines the first brilliant number, b_n, greater than 10^n. If n is odd or zero, then b_n is 10^n+a(n); and if n is a positive even number, then b_n is {10^(n/2)+a(n)}^2.

A084476.name: Least k such that 10^(2n-1)+k is a brilliant number.

A084477.name: Number of fault-free tilings of a 4 X 3n rectangle with right trominoes.
formula: G.f.: 9/2 - x - 1/Q(0) where Q(k)= 1 + 5^k/(1 - 2*x/(2*x + 5^k/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 10 2013

A084478.name: Number of tilings of a 5 X 3n rectangle with right trominoes.

A084479.name: Number of fault-free tilings of a 5 X 3n rectangle with right trominoes.

A084480.name: Number of tilings of a 4 X 2n rectangle with L tetrominoes.

A084481.name: Number of fault-free tilings of a 4 X 2n rectangle with L tetrominoes.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-3) for n>6. - _Colin Barker_, Mar 28 2017

A084482.name: Primes base 10 that remain primes in all nine bases b, 2<=b<=10, when the expansions are interpreted as decimal numbers.

A084483.name: If the rightmost block of zeros in binary representation of n has an even length, then delete one 0, otherwise insert one 0 in this block.

A084485.name: Number of 3 X n 0-1 matrices which have n+2 1's and have no zero rows or zero columns.

A084486.name: Number of 4 X n 0-1 matrices which have n+3 1's and have no zero rows or zero columns.

A084488.name: Prime(n)+q, where q is the next prime such that q mod 4 = (prime(n)+2) mod 4.

A084491.name: Permutation of Z, obtained by reflecting the juggling sequence A084501 from positive to negative numbers (with zero thrown at beat 0), folded to N with functions N2Z and Z2N.

A084502.name: Successively larger 3-ball ground-state site swaps of A084501 in concatenated decimal notation.

A084503.name: Binary juggling state vectors (given in decimal), associated with the three balls juggling sequence A084501.

A084506.name: The length of each successively larger 3-ball ground-state site swap given in A084501, i.e., the number of digits in each term of A084502.

A084507.name: First occurrence of n in A084501.

A084508.name: Partial sums of A084509. Positions of ones in the first differences of A084506.
formula: a(n) = n for n < 2, a(n) = 2^(2*n - 3) + 1 = A087289(n-2) for n >= 2. - _Antti Karttunen_, Oct 24 2012 [Corrected by _Petros Hadjicostas_, Aug 02 2020]

A084509.name: Number of ground-state 3-ball juggling sequences of period n.

A084510.name: a(0)=0, after which each n occurs A084516(n) times.

A084511.name: An infinite juggling sequence of three balls: successively larger indecomposable ground-state 3-ball site swaps listed in lexicographical order. A subset of A084501.

A084512.name: Successively larger 3-ball indecomposable ground-state site swaps of A084511 in concatenated decimal notation.

A084513.name: Juggling states associated with the juggling sequence A084511.

A084516.name: The length of each successively larger, indecomposable 3-ball ground-state site swap given in A084511, i.e., the number of digits in each term of A084512.

A084517.name: First occurrence of n in A084511.

A084518.name: Partial sums of A084519. Positions of ones in the first differences of A084516.

A084519.name: Number of indecomposable ground-state 3-ball juggling sequences of period n.
formula: a(n) seems to satisfy the recurrence: a(1) = a(2) = 1, a(3) = 3 and a(n) = 3*a(n-1)+2*a(n-2)+2*a(n-3). If so, a(n) = floor(A*B^n+1/2) where B = 3.6890953... is the real positive root of x^3-3x^2-2x-2 = 0 and A = 0.0687059... is the real positive root of 118*x^3+118*x^2+35*x-3 = 0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 14 2003 [This conjecture is established in the Chung-Graham paper.]

A084520.name: a(0)=0, after which each n occurs A084526(n) times.

A084521.name: An infinite juggling sequence of three balls: successively larger 'prime' ground-state 3-ball site swaps listed in lexicographical order. A subset of A084511.

A084522.name: Successively larger 3-ball 'prime' ground-state site swaps of A084521 in concatenated decimal notation.

A084523.name: Juggling states associated with the juggling sequence A084521.

A084526.name: The length of each successively larger, indecomposable, 'prime' 3-ball ground-state site swap given in A084521, i.e., the number of digits in each term of A084522.

A084527.name: First occurrence of n in A084521.

A084528.name: Partial sums of A084529. Positions of ones in the first differences of A084526.

A084529.name: Number of 'prime' ground-state 3-ball juggling sequences of period n.

A084534.name: Triangle read by rows: row #n has n+1 terms. T(n,0)=1, T(n,n)=2, T(n,m) = T(n-1,m-1) + Sum_{k=0..m} T(n-1-k,m-k).
formula: T(n,m) = binomial(2*n-m, m)*2*n/(2*n-m) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Dec 18 2017
Signed version: a(n,m)=0 if n<m, a(0,0)=1 else a(n,m)=((-1)^m)*binomial(2*n-m,m)*2*n/(2*n-m). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 07 2007
Signed version: a(n,m)=0 if n<m, a(0,0)=1 else a(n,m)=((-1)^m)*Sum_{l=0..n-m} binomial(m+l,l)*binomial(2*n,2*(l+m))/2^(2*(n-m)-1). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 07 2007

Signed version: a(n,m)=0 if n<m, a(0,0)=1 else a(n,m)= A127674(n,n-m)/2^(2*(n-m)-1) (scaled coefficients of Chebyshev's T(2*n,x)), decreasing even powers). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 07 2007; corrected by _Johannes W. Meijer_, May 31 2018

A084536.name: Triangular array related to Motzkin triangle A026300.

A084539.name: Continued fraction expansion of (negative of) Kinkelin constant.

A084540.name: a(n) is the algebraic order of the elliptic lambda function lambda^*(n), where lambda^*(n) is the value of k_n such that K'(k_n)/K(k_n) = sqrt(n), K(k) is a complete elliptic function and K'(k) is the complementary function.

A084541.name: Numbers n such that 4^n + 9i is a Gaussian Prime.

A084542.name: Numbers n such that 3^n + 10i is a Gaussian Prime.

A084544.name: Alternate number system in base 4.
formula: The formulas are designed to calculate base-10 numbers only using the digits 1..4.
a(n) <= (10^log_4(3*n+1)-1)/9, equality holds for n=(4^k-1)/3, k>0.
lim inf a(n)/10^log_4(3*n) = 2/45, for n --> infinity.
lim sup a(n)/10^log_4(3*n) = 1/9, for n --> infinity.

A084545.name: Alternate number system in base 5.
formula: The formulas are designed to calculate base-10 numbers only using the digits 1..5.
a(n) <= (10^log_5(4*n+1)-1)/9, equality holds for n=(5^k-1)/4, k>0.
lim inf a(n)/10^log_5(4*n) = 1/18, for n --> infinity.
lim sup a(n)/10^log_5(4*n) = 1/9, for n --> infinity.

A084546.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = C( C(n,2), k) for n >= 1, 0 <= k <= C(n,2).

A084547.name: Numbers n that have primitive roots less than n that are nonnegative perfect cubes.

A084548.name: Numbers n that have primitive roots less than n that are nonnegative perfect fifth powers.

A084549.name: Numbers n that have primitive roots less than n that are nonnegative perfect seventh powers.

A084550.name: Numbers n that have a primitive root less than n that are nonnegative perfect eleventh powers.

A084554.name: Weight distribution of [104,52,20] binary extended quadratic-residue (or QR) code.

A084555.name: Partial sums of A084556.
formula: a(0)=0; for n >= 1, a(n) = a(n-1) + A084556(n). Also a(n) = A130664(n+1) - 1. - _Antti Karttunen_, Dec 18 2012

A084557.name: a(0)=0, after which each n occurs A084556(n) times.

A084558.name: a(0) = 0; for n >= 1: a(n) = largest m such that n >= m!.
formula: The explicit first terms of the g.f. are: (x+x^2+x^6+x^24+x^120+x^720...)/(1-x).
For all n >= 0, a(n) = A090529(n+1) - 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 05 2014
For all n >= 1, a(n) = A060130(n) + A257510(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Apr 27 2015

A084559.name: Smallest a(n) > n such that concatenation of numbers from n to a(n) is a prime or 0 if no such number exists.

A084561.name: Numbers with a square number of 1's in their binary expansion.

A084562.name: Even numbers having no more than two partitions into two odd primes.

A084563.name: Even numbers having no more than three partitions into two odd primes.

A084564.name: Even numbers having no more than four partitions into two odd primes.

formula: G.f.: 1+ x -x/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + 3*x^2 + (3*k+4)*x - x*(3*k+1 + 3*x)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 07 2013

A084573.name: Let a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n)=nextprime( a(n-1)^(n/(n-1)) ).

A084574.name: Partial quotients of the continued fraction of e^(1/e).

A084575.name: Number of terms in polynomial expression for determinant of generic circulant matrix of order n.
formula: a(n) <= A003239(n), with = if n is a prime power. For other values of n little is known.

A084578.name: Positive integers not found in A084577.

A084580.name: Let y = m/GK(k), where m and k vary over the positive integers and GK(k)=log(1+1/(k*(k+2))/log(2) is the Gauss-Kuzmin distribution of k. Sort the y values by size and number them consecutively by n. This sequence gives the values of k in order by n.

A084584.name: Let y = m/GK(k), where m and k vary over the positive integers and GK(k)=log(1+1/(k*(k+2))/log(2) is the Gauss-Kuzmin distribution of k. Sort the y values by size and number them consecutively by n. This sequence gives the values of n when k=4.

A084585.name: Let y = m/GK(k), where m and k vary over the positive integers and GK(k)=log(1+1/(k*(k+2))/log(2) is the Gauss-Kuzmin distribution of k. Sort the y values by size and number them consecutively by n. This sequence gives the values of n when k=5.

A084586.name: Let y = m/GK(k), where m and k vary over the positive integers and GK(k)=log(1+1/(k*(k+2))/log(2) is the Gauss-Kuzmin distribution of k. Sort the y values by size and number them consecutively by n. This sequence gives the values of n when k=6.

A084591.name: Least positive integers, all distinct, that satisfy sum(n>0,1/a(n)^z)=0, where z is the fourth nontrivial zero of the Riemann Zeta function: z=(1/2 + i*y) with y=30.4248761258595132103118975...

A084593.name: Least positive integers, all distinct, that satisfy sum(n>0,1/a(n)^z)=0, where z is the 100th nontrivial zero of the Riemann Zeta function: z=(1/2 + i*y) with y=236.5242296658162058024755...

A084597.name: Largest k such that there are exactly n primes between k^2 and (k+1)^2.

A084598.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3; for n >= 2, a(n+1) is smallest prime factor of (Product_{k = 1..n} a(k)) - 1.

A084599.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3; for n >= 2, a(n+1) is largest prime factor of (Product_{k=1..n} a(k)) - 1.

A084600.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1+x+2x^2)^n for n>=0.
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/( 1 - x^(2*k+1)*(1+x+2*x^2)/(x^(2*k+1)*(1+x+2*x^2) + 1/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 06 2013

A084601.name: Coefficients of 1/(1-2x-7x^2)^(1/2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1+x+2x^2)^n.
formula: a(n)=sum{k=0..floor(n/2), binomial(n-k, k)binomial(n, k)2^k}. - _Paul Barry_, Aug 26 2004
Sum[k=0..n, Trinomial(k, n) Binomial(n, k) ], with Trinomial=A027907. - _Ralf Stephan_, Jan 28 2005

a(n) is also the central coefficient of (2+x+x^2)^n; a(n)=sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k) T(k,n), where T(k,n) is the triangle of trinomial coefficients = coefficient of x^n of (1+x+x^2)^k : A027907 - _N-E. Fahssi_, Feb 05 2008

A084602.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1 + x + 3x^2)^n.

A084603.name: Coefficients of 1/sqrt(1 - 2*x - 11*x^2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1 + x + 3*x^2)^n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k, k)*binomial(n, k)3^k. - _Paul Barry_, Aug 26 2004
Binomial transform is A084609. Hankel transform is 6^n*3^C(n,2). - _Paul Barry_, Sep 16 2006
a(n) is also the central coefficient of (3+x+x^2)^n;
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} 2^(n-k)*C(n,k)*T(k,n), where T(k,n) is the triangle of trinomial coefficients = coefficient of x^n of (1+x+x^2)^k: A027907. (End)
D-finite with recurrence: a(n+2) = ( (2*n+3)*a(n+1) + 11*(n+1)*a(n) )/(n+2); a(0)=a(1)=1. - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 01 2012
E.g.f.: exp(x)*BesselI(0, 2*sqrt(3)*x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 09 2014, after _Vladeta Jovovic_ in A084601

A084604.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1 + x + 4x^2)^n.

A084605.name: G.f.: 1/(1-2x-15x^2)^(1/2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1+x+4x^2)^n.
formula: a(n) is also the central coefficient of (4+x+x^2)^n; a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} 3^(n-k) C(n,k) T(k,n), where T(k,n) is the triangle of trinomial coefficients = Coefficient of x^n of (1+x+x^2)^k : A027907. - _N-E. Fahssi_, Mar 30 2008
D-finite with recurrence a(n+2) = ((2*n+3)*a(n+1) + 15*(n+1)*a(n))/(n+2); a(0)=a(1)=1 - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 01 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-3)^(n-k) * 2^k * binomial(n,k)*binomial(2*k,k). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 09 2018

A084606.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1+2x+2x^2)^n.

A084608.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1+2x+3x^2)^n.

A084609.name: Coefficients of 1/(1-4x-8x^2)^(1/2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1+2x+3x^2)^n.
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..floor(n/2), C(n,2*k)*C(2*k,k)*3^k*2^(n-2*k)}; a(n) = sum{k=0..floor(n/2), C(n,k)*C(n-k,k)*3^k*2^(n-2k)}. - _Paul Barry_, Sep 19 2006
a(n) = 2^n * hypergeom([(1-n)/2,-n/2], [1], 3) = binomial(2*n, n) * hypergeom([(1-n)/2,-n/2], [1/2-n], -2). - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Oct 10 2016

A084610.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1+x-x^2)^n.
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2 , where G(k)= 1 + 1/( 1 - (1+x-x^2)*x^(2*k+1)/((1+x-x^2)*x^(2*k+1) + 1/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 06 2013

A084611.name: a(n) = sum of absolute values of coefficients of (1+x-x^2)^n.

A084612.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1+x-2x^2)^n.

A084613.name: a(n) = sum of absolute values of coefficients of (1 + x - 2x^2)^n.

A084614.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th row lists the (2n+1) coefficients of (1 + x - 3x^2)^n.

A084615.name: a(n) = sum of absolute values of coefficients of (1+x-3x^2)^n.

A084616.name: Maximum number of circles of diameter 1 that can be packed in a square of area n (i.e., with side length n^(1/2)).

A084617.name: Maximum number of circles with diameter 1 that can be packed in a square of side length n.

A084618.name: Maximum number of circles of area 1 that can be packed in a circle of area n.

A084620.name: Numbers n such that concatenation of Fibonacci n and its 10's complement is a prime.

A084621.name: Numbers n such that Fibonacci(n) concatenated with its 10's complement is prime.

A084622.name: Numbers n such that f(n) is a strict local extremum for the function f(x) = phi(x) + sigma(x); i.e., either f(n) > f(n-1) and f(n) > f(n+1) or f(n) < f(n-1) and f(n) < f(n+1).

A084629.name: Brilliant numbers such that when they are concatenated with their 10's complement, which also must be brilliant, the result is a prime.

A084630.name: Floor(C(n+7,7)/C(n+5,5)).
formula: a(n) = a(-13-n) = a(n-21) +n+4 for all n in Z.

A084632.name: Semiprimes such that when they are concatenated with their 10's complement, which also must be a semiprime, the result is a prime.

A084633.name: Inverse binomial transform of repeated odd numbers.
formula: E.g.f.: (1 + 2*x + exp(-2*x))/2. - _Alejandro J. Becerra Jr._, Jan 29 2021

A084634.name: Binomial transform of 1,1,1,2,2,2,2,...
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} (2^i - i). - _Ctibor O. Zizka_, Oct 15 2010

A084639.name: Expansion of x*(1+2*x)/((1+x)*(1-x)*(1-2*x)).
formula: a(n) = a(n-2) + 2^n for n >= 2. - _Kensuke Matsuoka_, Aug 11 2020

A084640.name: Generalized Jacobsthal numbers.
formula: Le the array D(n,k) of the first differences be defined via D(0,k) = a(k); D(n+1,k) = D(n,k+1)-D(n,k).
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3), a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(2)=5. Observed by G. Detlefs. See the W. Lang link. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 18 2010

A084644.name: Best packings of m>1 equal circles into a larger circle setting a new density record.

A084645.name: Hypotenuses for which there exists a unique integer triangle.
formula: Terms are obtained by the products A004144(k)*A002144(p) for k, p > 0, ordered by increasing values. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Nov 12 2013

A084646.name: Hypotenuses for which there exist exactly 2 distinct integer triangles.
formula: Terms are obtained by the products A004144(k)*A002144(p)^2 for k, p > 0, ordered by increasing values. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Nov 12 2013

A084647.name: Hypotenuses for which there exist exactly 3 distinct integer triangles.
formula: Terms are obtained by the products A004144(k)*A002144(p)^3 for k, p > 0, ordered by increasing values. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Nov 12 2013

A084648.name: Hypotenuses for which there exist exactly 4 distinct integer triangles.

A084649.name: Hypotenuses for which there exist exactly 5 distinct integer triangles.
formula: Terms are obtained by the products A004144(k)*A002144(p)^5 for k, p > 0 ordered by increasing values. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Nov 12 2013

A084653.name: Pseudoprimes whose prime factors do not divide any smaller pseudoprime.

A084654.name: Smallest prime factor of pseudoprimes in A084653.

A084655.name: Largest prime factor of pseudoprimes in A084653.

A084656.name: Number of unlabeled connected claw-free cubic graphs on 2n vertices.

A084657.name: Number of unlabeled 2-connected claw-free cubic graphs on 2n vertices.

A084658.name: Number of unlabeled 3-connected claw-free cubic graphs on 2n vertices.

A084659.name: Number of labeled claw-free cubic graphs on 2n nodes (not necessarily connected).
formula: Recurrence is given in Maple code below. For asymptotics see the 2003 paper.

A084660.name: Decimal expansion of solution of area bisectors problem.

A084661.name: Numbers k such that k + sum_of_digits(k) is a cube.

A084666.name: Lunar primes that are also rational primes.

A084667.name: Primes which are a concatenation of n and prime(n).

A084668.name: Brilliant Niven numbers, i.e., numbers with two prime factors of the same length (in decimal notation) which are also divisible by the sum of their digits.

A084669.name: Primes which are a concatenation of prime(n) and n.

A084670.name: Numbers k such that concatenation of prime(k) and k is prime.

A084671.name: Primes such that the decimal concatenation of prime(n) and n is prime.

A084673.name: Smallest prime in which a digit appears n times.

A084674.name: Products of the digits of e excluding 0.

A084675.name: Product of the first n digits of the Golden Ratio phi = 1.6180339... (treating 0's as if they were 1's).

A084676.name: Position of the first zero in the decimal expansion of the square root of the n-th prime.

A084677.name: Position of the first zero in the decimal expansion of sqrt(n).

A084678.name: a(n)=b(n,n) with b(n,1)=n and b(n,k)=binomial(b(n,k-1),d(n,n-k+1)) for 1<k<=n, where d(n,i) are the divisors of n, d(i)<d(j), 1<=i<j<=A000005(n).

A084679.name: Composite numbers with coprime numbers of prime factors with and without repetition.

A084680.name: Order of 10 modulo n [i.e., least m such that 10^m = 1 (mod n)] or 0 when no such number exists.

A084681.name: Order of 10 modulo 9n [i.e., least m such that 10^m = 1 (mod 9n)] or 0 when no such number exists.
formula: If n is not divisible by 3, a(n) = A084680(n).
Otherwise a(n) can be either A084680(n), 3*A084680(n) or 9*A084680(n). (End)

A084682.name: Even evil numbers with an even digital sum.

A084684.name: Degrees of certain maps.
formula: a(n) = a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015
a(n) - a(n-1) = A001651(n), a(n+1) - a(n-1) = 3*n for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015
(a(n) - a(n+1))^2 - (2*a(n) + a(n+1)) + 4 = 3*n/2 + 1 for all even n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015
0 = -4 + a(n)*(-a(n+1) + a(n+2)) + a(n+1)*(+3 + a(n+1) - a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015
A122958(n-1) = p(-1) where p(x) is the unique degree-n polynomial such that p(k) = a(k) for k = 0, 1, ..., n for all n>1. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015

A084685.name: a(n) is the least x such that length of fixed-point-list when function-A085307[] was iterated and started at a(n) equals n.

A084686.name: Take n-th prime p(n), rewrite it with digits in decreasing order to get b(n), then a(n)=(b(n)-p(n))/9.

A084687.name: Nontrivial numbers k containing no zero digits which are divisible by the number formed by writing the digits of k in ascending order.

A084688.name: Nonnegative integers n such that 2^n uses only distinct decimal digits.

A084691.name: 10000 times the n-th zero of the BesselJ function of zero order, rounded.

A084692.name: Sum of first n zeros of BesselJ function of zero order.

A084693.name: a(n) is smallest positive integer not already in the sequence such that every partial sum is squarefree.

A084694.name: Squarefree numbers which are products of three consecutive numbers. I.e., squarefree numbers of the form k^3 - k.

A084695.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n contains the n smallest (greater than zero) numbers such that when they are incremented by n yield a prime.

A084696.name: Beginning with 3, primes such that a(2n) = {a(2n-1) +a(2n+1)}/2.

A084697.name: a(1) = 2; for n >= 1, k>=1, a(n+1) = a(n) + k*n is the smallest such prime.

A084698.name: Beginning with 1 the smallest multiple of n such that the n-th partial sum is a square.
formula: For n>16, a(n) = 48n if n is odd, 96n if n is even.

A084699.name: Composite integers n such that binomial(2*n,n)==2^n (mod n).

A084700.name: Smallest k such that k*prime(i)+1 is prime for i = 1 to n.

A084701.name: Smallest k such that k*prime(i)-1 is prime for i = 1 to n.

A084702.name: a(n) = smallest k such that k+1 and n*k+1 both are perfect squares, or 0 if no such number exists.
formula: a(i^2-1) is usually (i-1)^2-1. For 2 < i < 1000 there are 34 exceptions. The first four of these are a(11^2-1) = 3, a(23^2-1) = 8, a(39^2-1) = 15 and a(41^2-1) = 3. - _David Wasserman_, May 03 2007

A084703.name: Squares n such that 2*n+1 is also a square.
formula: Empirical: for n>0, a(n) = A089928(4*n-2). - _Alex Ratushnyak_, Apr 12 2013

A084704.name: Smallest prime p > prime(n) such that (p + prime(n))/2 is prime.

A084708.name: Number of set partitions up to rotations and reflections.

A084709.name: a(1) = 4, for n > 1, a(n) = smallest multiple of a(n-1) such that a(n)-1 and a(n)+1 are twin primes.

A084710.name: Beginning with 2 the smallest prime greater than the previous term such that the difference of successive terms is a distinct square.

A084711.name: -21*zeta_K(-1), where K runs through the simplest cubic fields.

A084712.name: Smallest prime of the form (2n)^k +1, or 0 if no such number exists.

A084713.name: Smallest prime of the form (2n-1)^k + 2, or 0 if no such number exists.

A084714.name: a(n) = smallest prime of the form (2n-1)^k - 2, or 0 if no such number exists.

A084715.name: Smallest number of the form n*k + 1 that is divisible by all the phi(n) numbers less than n and relatively prime to n.

A084716.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest multiple of a(n-1) > a(n-1) such that a(n) + 1 is a prime.

A084717.name: a(1) = 3 then a(n) = smallest multiple of a(n-1) > a(n-1) such that a(n) - 1 is a prime.

A084719.name: 8190*zeta_K(-3), where K runs through the simplest cubic fields.

A084720.name: Primes p such that p+1 is a product of two or more consecutive integers.

A084723.name: Primes arising in A083566. a(n) = n-th partial product of A083566 + 2.

A084724.name: Beginning with 2, the smallest even number greater than the previous term such that every partial product + 1 is a prime.

A084725.name: Primes arising in A084724. a(n) = N-th partial product of A084724 +1.

A084726.name: Smallest common difference of the arithmetic progression of length n, beginning with 1 whose product of first n terms + 1 is a prime.

A084728.name: a(n) = smallest multiple of n such that a(1)*a(2)*...*a(n) + 1 is a prime.

A084730.name: Smallest prime of the form k*n! - 1.

A084732.name: Let p be the n-th prime; Cp(x) be the p-th cyclotomic polynomial (x^p-1)/(x-1); a(n) is the first prime Cp(x) after Cp(1).

A084733.name: Squares which are the sum of at least three successive terms of a geometric progression.

A084734.name: -3591*zeta_K(-5), where K runs through the simplest cubic fields.

A084735.name: Let p = n-th prime, let q = smallest prime having p as its least prime primitive root; sequence gives least (not necessarily prime) primitive root of q.

A084736.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3; for n > 0, a(n+2) is the smallest prime chosen so that (a(n+2) - a(n+1))/(a(n+1) - a(n)) is an integer.

A084738.name: Smallest prime of the form (n^k-1)/(n-1), or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084739.name: Let p = n-th prime, then a(n) = smallest prime having p as its least prime primitive root.

A084740.name: Least k such that (n^k-1)/(n-1) is prime, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084741.name: Smallest prime of the form (n^k+1)/(n+1), or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084742.name: Least k such that (n^k+1)/(n+1) is prime, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084743.name: Smallest prime of the form n^k + k, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084744.name: Product of all composite numbers from 1 to the n-th nonprime number divided by product of all the prime divisors of each of those composite numbers which exceed the previously stated value.

A084745.name: Smallest prime of the form n^k - k, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A084746.name: Smallest k such that n^k - k is a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.

A084747.name: Leading diagonal of triangle shown below in which the n-th row contains the n smallest numbers > 0 such that when they are incremented by n yield a prime.
formula: a(n) = prime(primepi(n) + n) - n. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Mar 22 2021

A084748.name: Primes of the form n! + p where p is the smallest prime > n.

A084749.name: Numbers n such that n! + p is a prime, where p is the smallest prime > n.

A084750.name: Numbers n such that n! - p is a prime, where p is the smallest prime > n.

A084751.name: Primes of the form k! - p, where p is the smallest prime > k.

A084752.name: A064623(n)/s, where s = sum of the prime divisors of A064623(n).

A084754.name: Triangle read by rows: row n contains the first n primes greater than n.

A084755.name: Let the sequence s_n be defined by s_n(1) = n+1 and for k > 1, s_n(k) = k*s_n(k-1)+1. Then a(n) is the first prime in the sequence s_n.

A084756.name: For n, k > 0, let T(n, k) be given by T(n, 1) = n and T(n, k+1) = k*T(n, k)+1. Then a(n) = T(n, n).

A084757.name: For n, k > 0, let T(n, k) be given by T(n, 1) = n and T(n, k+1) = k*T(n, k)+1. a(n) is the sum of the n-th antidiagonal.

A084758.name: The slowest increasing sequence of primes such that difference of successive terms is unique.

A084759.name: Composite numbers in ascending order such that difference of successive terms is unique. a(m)-a(m-1) = a(k)-a(k-1) iff m = k.

A084760.name: Squarefree numbers in ascending order such that difference of successive terms is unique. a(m)-a(m-1) = a(k)-a(k-1) iff m = k.

A084761.name: Primes such that {a(m)-a(m-1)}/{a(m-1)-a(m-2)} is a unique integer.

A084765.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1)^2 - 1, a(0)=1, a(1)=5.
formula: 4*sqrt(6)/11 = Product_{n >= 1} (1 - 1/(2*a(n))). See A002812 for some general properties of the recurrence a(n+1) = 2*a(n)^2 - 1. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 11 2012

A084766.name: Sum of numbers of prime-factors {2*n-p: 2<p<2*n, p prime}, with repetitions.

A084767.name: Number of distinct prime-factors of {2*n-p: 2<p<2*n, p prime}.

A084768.name: P_n(7), where P_n is n-th Legendre polynomial; also, a(n) = central coefficient of (1 + 7*x + 12*x^2)^n.
formula: Also a(n) = (n+1)-th term of the binomial transform of 1/(1-3x)^(n+1).
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 7*(1-2*n)*a(n-1) + (n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 27 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k)^2 * 3^k * 4^(n-k). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 28 2012

A084769.name: P_n(9), where P_n is n-th Legendre polynomial; also, a(n) = central coefficient of (1 + 9*x + 20*x^2)^n.
formula: Also a(n) = (n+1)-th term of the binomial transform of 1/(1-4x)^(n+1).
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 9*(1-2*n)*a(n-1) + (n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 27 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)^2 * 4^k * 5^(n-k). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 29 2012
x*exp(Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/n) = x + 9*x^2 + 101*x^3 + 1269*x^4 + ... is an integral power series, the o.g.f. for A269732. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 25 2018

A084770.name: Coefficients of 1/(1-4x-16x^2)^(1/2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1+2x+5x^2)^n.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(2*x)*BesselI(0, 2*sqrt(5)*x). More generally, e.g.f.: exp(b*x)*BesselI(0, 2*sqrt(c)*x) yields central coefficients of (1+b*x+c*x^2)^n. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 21 2004
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n, k)*binomial(2(n-k), n)*4^k. - _Paul Barry_, Sep 08 2004
Define Q(n, x) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n, k)*binomial(2(n-k), n)*x^(n-2k). A084770(n) is 2^n*Q(n, 1/2). - _Paul Barry_, Sep 08 2004

A084771.name: Coefficients of expansion of 1/sqrt(1 - 10*x + 9*x^2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1 + 5*x + 4*x^2)^n.
formula: Binomial transform of A059304. G.f.: Sum_{k>=0} binomial(2*k, k)*(2*x)^k/(1-x)^(k+1). E.g.f.: exp(5*x)*BesselI(0, 4*x). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 20 2003
a(n) = sum(k=0..n, sum(j=0..n-k, C(n,j)*C(n-j,k)*C(2*n-2*j,n-j) ) ). - _Paul Barry_, May 19 2006
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 5*(-2*n+1)*a(n-1) + 9*(n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 26 2012
a(n) = -3 * 9^n * a(-1-n) for all n in Z.

A084772.name: Coefficients of 1/sqrt(1 - 12*x + 16*x^2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1 + 6*x + 5*x^2)^n.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 6*(1-2*n)*a(n-1) + 16*(n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 09 2012

A084773.name: Coefficients of 1/sqrt(1-12*x+4*x^2); also, a(n) is the central coefficient of (1+6x+8x^2)^n.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(6x)*Bessel_I(0, 2*sqrt(8)*x); a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} C(n, k)*C(2(n-k), n)*(-1)^k*3^(n-2k). - _Paul Barry_, May 30 2005
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + 6*(-2*n+1)*a(n-1) + 4*(n-1)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 30 2012

formula: # The operator DELTA takes two sequences r = (r_0, r_1, ...), s = (s_0, s_1, ...) and produces a triangle T(n, k), 0 <= k <= n, as follows:

Let q(k) = x*r_k + y*s_k for k >= 0; let P(n, k) (n >= 0, k >= -1) be defined recursively by P(0, k) = 1 for k >= 0; P(n, -1) = 0 for n >= 1; P(n, k) = P(n, k-1) + q(k)*P(n-1, k+1) for n >= 1, k >= 0.
Then P(n, k) is a homogeneous polynomial in x and y of degree n and T(n, k) = coefficient of x^(n-k)*y^k in P(n, 0).
T(m+n, m)= Sum_{k=0..n} A090238(n, k)*binomial(m, k).
G.f. for column k: Sum_{n>=0} T(k+n, k)*x^n = (Sum_{n>=0} n!*x^n )^k.

A084950.name: Array of coefficients of denominator polynomials of the n-th approximation of the continued fraction x/(1+x/(2+x/(3+..., related to Laguerre polynomial coefficients.
formula: Recurrence (short version): a(n,m) = n*a(n-1,m) + a(n-2,m-1), n>=1, a(0,0) =1, a(n,-1) = 0, a(n,m) = 0 if n < 2*m. From the recurrence for the Q(n,x) polynomials given in a comment above.

Recurrence (long version): a(n,m) = (2*(n-m)-1)*a(n-1,m) + a(n-2,m-1) - (n-m-1)^2*a(n-2,m), n >= 1, a(0,0) =1, a(n,-1) = 0,  a(n,m) =0 if n < 2*m. From the standard three term recurrence for the unsigned orthogonal Laguerre polynomials. This recurrence can be simplified to the preceding one, because of the explicit factorial formula given above which follows from the one for the Laguerre coefficients (which, in turn, derives from the Rodrigues formula and the Leibniz rule). This proves the relation a(n,m) = |Lhat(n-m,m)|, with the coefficients |Lhat(n,m)| = |A021009(n,m)| of the unsigned n!*L(n,x) Laguerre polynomials.
For the e.g.f.s of the column sequences see  A021009 (here with different offset, which could be obtained by integration).

E.g.f. for row polynomials gQ(z,x) := Sum_{z>=0} Q(n,x)*z^n = (i*Pi*sqrt(x)/sqrt(1-z))*(BesselJ(1, 2*i*sqrt(x)*sqrt(1-z))*BesselY(0, 2*i*sqrt(x)) - BesselY(1, 2*i*sqrt(x)*sqrt(1-z))*BesselJ(0,2*i*sqrt(x))), with the imaginary unit i = sqrt(-1) and Bessel functions. (End)

The row polynomials are Q(n,x) = Pi*(z/2)^(n+1)*(BesselY(0,z)*BesselJ(n+1,z) - BesselJ(0,z)*BesselY(n+1,z)) with z := -i*2*sqrt(x), and the imaginary unit i. An alternative form is Q(n,x) = 2*(w/2)^(n+1)*(BesselI(0,w)*BesselK(n+1,w) - BesselK(0,w)*BesselI(n+1,w)*(-1)^(n+1)) with w := -2*sqrt(x). See A221913 for the derivation based on Abramowitz-Stegun's Handbook. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 06 2013
Lim_{n -> infinity} Q(n,x)/n! = BesselI(0,2*sqrt(x)). See a comment on asymptotics above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 07 2013
